Hey, it's me! 
I'm Dawn, the dyer, designer, and creative force behind Barker Wool and Dawn Barker Designs.
My favorite part about my job is that I get to be part of the creative continuum. I create so that you can be creative too! ✨

I'm blessed to be married to my best friend, Dale, (21 years tomorrow), and to be the mom of the two greatest boys a person could ever hope for. 

I've been knitting and crocheting since I was seven, and I love to try and find new ways to bend yarn.  I'm a huge color nerd and will talk your ear off about color theory and pattern if you give me the chance. 

Being a part of this community brings great joy into my life.  I'm glad to be here and just as glad that you are too. Chime in below and say hello!

New for #FOFriday! 

I'm kinda amazed at how many of you messaged me about the teaser picture of this sweater, so I'm pleased to introduce The Language Of Fans! 

Before you ask, I literally just took this off the blocking mats on Tuesday, so I still need to finish writing the pattern and send it to my  lovely tech editor before I can announce a testing call. 

By popular demand, I'll also be writing a shawl version of it too. 

Now for the particulars: 
She is a boxy-fitting, dropped shoulder, boat neck pullover with 3/4 length sleeves. 
I used 2 skeins of my assigned pooling colorway Dolce and 2 skeins of my tonal colorway Blue Agave. 

She's a great example of my new stitch collab between AP & lace.  I'll be teaching this technique in my Knit Stars masterclass, so go sign up using the link in my bio if you're interested. Preorders for season 8 close on Sunday, so don't wait!

Are you ready?✨🪇

Join the Bossa Nova KAL and cast on with me! 

Bossa Nova is a delightful Aran weight shawl made in your four favorite colors. Because of its gauge, it flies off the needles in no time, so you'll be able to finish one, (or two or three...), well before the temperatures cool down again. 

Are you new to slipped stitch colorwork? I've got you covered! 
Join me this Saturday,June 3 on Zoom hosted by @hillcountryweavers to learn everything you need to know. 
(Sign up on their website.) 

What you need: Five 100g skeins of Barker Wool Merinolux Aran in four colors of your choice. (Color #2 makes the border too, so two skeins are needed.)

I'm using, clockwise from the top, Doe, Tin Roof, Octobers, & Steadfast because I can't wait to wear this first thing in October, but any four colors you like will be beautiful together. 

To participate in the KAL, simply follow me, @barker.wool, and tag your progress photos with #BossaNovaShawl & #BarkerWoolSummerKAL. 

Prizes? If course! I'll pick three winners from the tagged completed shawl photos on July 31.

I used Petal and Boro for the original, but any color combination you prefer will work beautifully.

Ready for an engaging knitting adventure?  I've made Llano at least five times, and its pooling pattern has been surprising each time! 

Llano, (pronounced Yah'-no),is an assigned pooling pullover knit in one piece from cuff to cuff. It features my sprout stitch on a background of stockinette. The magic happens when the row length changes as the sweater is shaped, thus changing the pooling dispersion into bending and waving lines.  Each Llano is unique!

I used Ultraviolet on BFL for this one, but any of my assigned pooling colorways would work beautifully.

Are you ready to cast on The Language Of Fans but don't know what colors to choose? 

I get lots of questions about choosing, so here are the things you need to know:

1. Pick any AP color that strikes your fancy.

2. Before choosing the tonal companion, think about how bold or subtle you want your stripes to be. 
For bold stripes like the ones pictured here, choose a tonal companion with high contrast to the background color of the AP colorway. 
For subtle stripes, choose a tonal companion that matches or blends with the background of the AP colorway.

3. Now think about how that tonal companion gets along with the accent color in the AP colorway.  The AP accent will blend in and disappear if it is too similar to the tonal companion, so be sure they don't look too much like each other.

4. When in doubt, pick a neutral!  Choosing a neutral as the tonal companion will almost always give you the balance you're looking for. 
If your AP accent happens to be neutral too, just be sure to pick a neutral tonal that is lighter or darker than the AP accent. 

I used Grasshopper as my AP and Steadfast as its tonal companion for bold stripes. 
I would have chosen Serenade or Mushroom if I had wanted to dial down the intensity of the stripes.

Are you still on the fence about signing up for  Knit Stars Season 8?✨
Here are my top 10 reasons why I think you should join!

1. Learn assigned pooling from its creator!  Come virtually to my home and get a glimpse into my creative process.  I’ll show you all the ins and outs to give you the inside track on assigned pooling.  

2.  AP Stitch Index.  See me demonstrate all of my current AP stitches. I break each one down to make them easy to learn.

3.  AP Garments.  Learn all of my best tricks on how to apply assigned pooling to sweaters.  

4.  Stitch Collabs.  Go beyond the floret cluster and see the next generation of this new and innovative technique.  

5.  Exclusive Access.  Each Knit Star created a special pattern to go along with their masterclass.  By signing up, you get not only this special collection of patterns but also access to yarn created especially for each one by our Star Maker partners.   

6.  Variety.  Learn from 10 (TEN!) different Knit Star masterclasses in a wide variety of topics.  

7.  Production Quality. Are you a visual learner?  Knit Stars’ high production standards mean you can clearly see every detail and never miss a stitch. 

8. Community.  Come home to the mothership and meet tons of other folks that share your yarn obsession! 

9.Value. You get forever access to all ten Season 8 masterclasses, so you can watch, rewind, slow down, and watch again to your heart’s content! 

10.  Curiosity.  I saved my favorite for last.  Did you know that learning new skills not only lets you create beautiful, practical pieces of wearable art but also helps keep your brain healthy?  Stretch yourself a little, learn something new, and keep your brain in good shape in the process!  

Are you ready to sign up?  I would appreciate it if you used the link in my profile so I get credit for you joining the party!  Thank you! ✨🎉

Ostinato, A Knitted Advent Wrap ✨

Ostinato is a musical term used to describe a continually repeated musical phrase or rhythm.  I’m borrowing it here to describe the rhythm of the colored blocks that are repeated in a regular pattern across the length of this elegant rectangular Advent wrap. The main body is knit in simple stamen stitch using 24 colors, creating a subtle texture that allows the carefully curated  color story of the Advent set to take center stage.

Agnes, A Crocheted Advent Wrap 
is my crocheted pattern for Advent'23. 

On Christmas morning in 1975, my paternal grandmother, Agnes, gave my sister and me matching twin-sized Catherine Wheel afghans crocheted in four shades of pink acrylic, ranging from pale petal to bright bubblegum. Catherine Wheel has been my favorite crochet pattern ever since. I love its simple repeating circles and how it fills my heart with memories of simpler times spent watching my grandmother, hook in hand, flowing with ease through every stitch.  Agnes is my tribute to her and a small thank you for all she taught me. I updated the color palette and shape, and used a butter-soft Merino blend, but everything I loved about the rhythm of the circles is still there in spades.

Find the pattern on my website and on Ravelry.

Salem's Path is the third pattern for Advent'23.✨

Salem's Path is a generously-sized triangular shawl in a rainbow of twenty-five colors. It’s made using a simple slipped stitch colorwork technique that is easy to memorize and follow. 

The rhythmic slip sequence is constant throughout, and the color progression flows through all twenty-five colors and then back again through a portion of the first ones for balanced movement across the piece. 

The shawl is designed to be used with an Advent set, but it would also make a lovely memory shawl using remnants. The rhythmic slipped stitch colorwork technique creates a beautiful and intricate pattern, and its methodical nature makes it a relaxing and meditative project to work on.
